\description{
\code{est_pw()} constructs and validates the objects required for
pseudo-weights estimation using one or more reference probability surveys.
The function prepares the participation model, processes missing values in
participation variables, estimates pseudo-weights, and stores intermediate
quantities needed for downstream point estimation and variance calculation.

Users should harmonize variable names and coding before calling
\code{est_pw()}. Variables used in the participation model must have
consistent names and compatible definitions across the nonprobability sample
and the relevant reference survey or surveys.

With one reference sample, the available methods include the adjusted
logistic propensity weighting method proposed by
Wang, Valliant, and Li (2021), the CLW method proposed by
Chen, Li, and Wu (2020), and the raking-ratio calibration
method described in Landsman et al. (2026).

With multiple reference samples, pseudo-weights are estimated using the
multi-reference raking procedure proposed by Landsman et al. (2026),
which integrates multiple reference probability surveys through a
system of calibration estimating equations.

The returned object is designed to be passed to \code{\link{pwmean}}.
}
\details{
\code{est_pw()} separates pseudo-weights estimation from outcome estimation.
It does not require an outcome variable. Instead, it focuses on constructing
pseudo-weights for the nonprobability sample and saving the method-specific
internal objects needed later by \code{\link{pwmean}}.

The input \code{data} must be a list whose first element is the
nonprobability sample and whose remaining elements are reference survey design
objects.

Variable names are matched by name, not by meaning. For example, if age
category is called \code{agecat} in the nonprobability sample and
\code{age_group} in a reference survey, the user should rename one of the
variables before fitting the model. Factor levels and category definitions
should also be made compatible before estimation.

Internally, \code{est_pw()}:

\enumerate{
  \item validates the input structure, including \code{sc_wname} (must be a
    single non-empty string that does not already exist as a column in
    \code{sc}), \code{verbose} (must be a single \code{TRUE}/\code{FALSE}),
    and all reference sample data frames (must have at least one row);
  \item determines whether the problem is a one-reference or multi-reference case;
  \item resolves the pseudo-weighting method;
  \item constructs a default participation formula if \code{p_formula = NULL};
  \item processes missing values in variables used by the participation model;
  \item extracts and processes participation model covariates;
  \item estimates pseudo-weights using the selected method;
  \item reconstructs the output nonprobability sample with a pseudo-weight column;
  \item stores NA-handling information and internal build objects.
