\section{One-reference and multi-reference cases}{

If \code{data} contains exactly one reference survey design object,
\code{est_pw()} fits a one-reference pseudo-weighting method. The argument
\code{method} must be one of \code{"alp"}, \code{"clw"},
\code{"calibration"}, or \code{"cali"}.

If \code{data} contains more than one reference survey design object, the
problem is treated as a multi-reference problem. In this case, \code{method}
is resolved to \code{"multi"}, and the function estimates pseudo-weights
using the multi-reference raking method. In both cases, the auxiliary
variables used for pseudo-weights estimation should be harmonized across the
nonprobability sample and the relevant reference surveys before calling
\code{est_pw()}.
}

\section{Multi-reference pre-calibration}{

When \code{precali = TRUE}, cumulative pre-calibration is performed before the
main multi-reference pseudo-weights estimation step. This step aligns
overlapping auxiliary information across reference samples before constructing
the stacked multi-reference calibration equations.

The order of the reference samples is controlled by \code{sp_order}. If
\code{sp_order = "size"}, reference samples are ordered by sample size, from
largest to smallest. If \code{sp_order = "given"}, the order supplied by the
user in \code{data} is used.

Pre-calibration uses only the variables that appear in \code{p_formula},
specifically the intersection of the formula variables across all reference
surveys. This ensures that the pre-calibration step aligns reference samples
on exactly the same dimensions used in the participation models.
}

\section{Missing data handling}{

Missing values are handled at the build step only for variables involved in
the participation model. The selected \code{na.action} is recorded in the
returned object, together with the row indices of the nonprobability sample
observations retained for fitting.

This behavior is designed to mimic the style of model-fitting functions such
as \code{lm()}. With \code{stats::na.omit}, rows with missing
participation model variables are removed from \code{sc_updated}. With
\code{stats::na.exclude}, the original rows are retained in
\code{sc_updated}, but excluded rows receive \code{NA} in the pseudo-weight
column.
}

\section{Numerical control}{

Numerical settings are supplied through the \code{control} argument, which
should usually be created by \code{\link{pw_solver_control}}. This object
controls solver choice, convergence tolerance, maximum iterations, tracing,
and optional solver-specific arguments.

The top-level \code{ftol}, \code{xtol}, and \code{maxit} values in
\code{\link{pw_solver_control}} are the package-level convergence controls
used by pseudo-weights estimation stages. When the selected solver is
\code{"nleqslv"}, additional arguments can be passed through
\code{nleqslv_control}. These are forwarded to \code{nleqslv::nleqslv()}.
}

